{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537709","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537709"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:19:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:19:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16042"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16042","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16042"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.01,0.62,0.22,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8733"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63660"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8733","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8733"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16042"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49108"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"188"},{"type":"tags","id":"1306"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3177"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20877"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48073"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63660","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63660"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with her parent with a two-month history of unusual experiences. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She denies using alcohol or illicit substances.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears anxious but cooperative with vital signs within normal limits. During the mental state examination, she describes experiencing distressing thoughts about harming others that she does not believe are her own. She also reports that sometimes she feels her actions are being controlled by external forces. She is deeply troubled by these experiences but remains insightful that they are unusual.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the predominant psychotic phenomenon in this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thought broadcasting","Thought withdrawal","Thought insertion","Thought control","Obsessive intrusive thoughts"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a complex picture with multiple overlapping phenomena, requiring careful phenomenological analysis to identify the predominant feature. The key distinguishing feature of \u003Cstrong\u003Ethought insertion\u003C/strong\u003E is the experience of thoughts being placed into one\u0027s mind by an external agency, with these thoughts being experienced as alien and not belonging to the person. This is the central phenomenon described by the patient, who clearly articulates that the thoughts \u0027appear\u0027 and are \u0027being put there by someone else.\u0027\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThought broadcasting\u003C/strong\u003E involves the belief that one\u0027s thoughts are being transmitted to others, which is not described in this case. While the patient has multiple unusual experiences, there is no suggestion that her thoughts are being transmitted to or heard by others.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThought withdrawal\u003C/strong\u003E may be present as a secondary phenomenon when she describes thoughts disappearing suddenly, but this is not the predominant feature of her presentation. The primary experience is of thoughts being inserted rather than withdrawn.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThought control\u003C/strong\u003E is suggested by her experience of actions being controlled by external forces, but this represents a separate phenomenon from the primary experience of thought insertion. While both are passivity phenomena, they are distinct experiences.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObsessive intrusive thoughts\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered given the content (thoughts of harm) and the patient\u0027s insight, but these differ fundamentally from thought insertion. In obsessive-compulsive disorder, while thoughts are unwanted and distressing, they are still recognised as being generated by one\u0027s own mind, unlike the alien quality described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis case highlights the complexity of psychotic phenomena, where multiple symptoms often co-exist. The presence of insight does not exclude psychosis, and careful attention must be paid to the phenomenology rather than just the content of thoughts. The temporal progression and presence of other symptoms would be important in establishing the underlying diagnosis, as thought insertion can occur in various conditions including schizophrenia, acute psychotic episodes, and other psychiatric disorders.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Thought insertion must be distinguished from intrusive thoughts in obsessive-compulsive disorder, where thoughts are unwanted but recognised as self-generated.","The presence of thought insertion alone is insufficient to diagnose schizophrenia - a comprehensive assessment of other symptoms and time course is essential.","Passivity phenomena often co-exist and careful phenomenological assessment is needed to identify the predominant feature."],"references":["Benjamin JS, Kaplan SJ. Sadock Comprehensive Textbook of Psychiatry."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49108"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16042"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49108","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49108"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-22T04:32:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-22T04:33:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8733"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63660"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"188","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/188"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Psychotic disorders","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-